http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: Social factors such as personal behavior, lifestyle, or environment belonging to the subject which are known to increase the likelihood of infection and disease.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_P325.@value: Social factors such as personal behavior, lifestyle, or environment belonging to the subject which are known to increase the likelihood of infection and disease.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: Any factor, such as age, ethnicity, genetic factor, family history, or environmental factor, that increases a person's chance of developing melanoma.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A risk factor is a variable that has a potential association with a response variable.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: Health hazards at home, in the work place, or in nature (e.g., infectious agents, irritants, respiratory fibrotic agents, asphyxiants, allergens, metabolic poisons, physical agents, mutagens, teratogens, and carcinogens). (Winett et al: Health Psychology and Public Health)
Increase in the chance of developing a disease, due to hormonal factors.
A characteristic of an organism that contributes to the diagnosis or treatment of a disease or to the prediction of clinical outcomes.
Any factor, such as age, ethnicity, genetic factor, family history, over-exposure to estrogen, or environmental factors, that increases a person's chance of developing breast cancer.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_P375.@value: Other specified personal risk factors, not elsewhere classified

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: A numerical scale used to compare variables with one another or with some reference number; a number used to select an element of a list, vector, array or other sequence.
The distinguishing qualities or prominent aspect of a person, object, action, process, or substance.
Something that is a necessary condition; something that is obligatory.
An ordered reference standard used to measure incremental changes.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A data type is the type of response variable data.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: An extrapolation of given data into the future.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: An exception is the variable name in risk factor tables that have names that look like risk factors but arenâ€™t.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_00001.@value: A prominent or identifiable aspect, region, or site of interest.
The outcome of an experiment or set of experiments, including observations and primary, processed, and analyzed data.
A combination of symbols that represents a value.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A variable specification that specifies a variable that may have a causal impact on both the independent variable and dependent variable; ignoring a confounding variable may bias empirical estimates of the causal effect of the independent variable.
A quantitative confidence value that represents the probability of obtaining a result at least as extreme as that actually obtained, assuming that the actual value was the result of chance alone.

A quantitative confidence value resulting from a multiple testing error correction method which adjusts the p-value used as input to control for Type I error in the context of multiple pairwise tests.
A planned process that produces output data from input data.

A logarithmic transformation is a data transformation consisting in the application of the logarithm function with a given base a (where a>0 and a is not equal to 1) to a (one dimensional) positive real number input. The logarithm function with base a can be defined as the inverse of the exponential function with the same base. See e.g. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm.

The standard error of the mean (SEM) is data item denoting the standard deviation of the sample-mean's estimate of a population mean.It is calculated by dividing the sample standard deviation (i.e., the sample-based estimate of the standard deviation of the population) by the square root of n , the size (number of observations) of the sample.
Statistical sample size is a count evaluating the number of individual experimental units.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: linear regression for analysis of continuous dependent variable

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Linear regression model is a model which attempts to explain data distribution associated with response/dependent variable in terms of values assumed by the independent variable uses a linear function or linear combination of the regression parameters and the predictor/independent variable(s).Linear regression modeling makes a number of assumptions, which includes homoskedasticity (constance of variance).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: binomial logistic regression for analysis of dichotomous dependent variable

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binomial logistic regression model is a model which attempts to explain data distribution associated with *dichotomous* response/dependent variable in terms of values assumed by the independent variable uses a function of predictor/independent variable(s): the function used in this instance of regression modeling is logistic function.

Variable distribution is data item which denotes the spatial resolution of data point making up a variable. variable distribution may be compared to a known probability distribution using goodness of fit test or plotting a quantile-quantile plot for visual assessment of the fit.

is a population whose individual members realize (may be expressed as) a combination of  inclusion rule values specifications or resulting from a sampling process (e.g. recruitment followed by randomization to group) on which a number of measurements will be carried out, which may be used as input to statistical tests and statistical inference.
a cohort is a study group population where the members are human beings which meet inclusion criteria and undergo a longitudinal design
A normal distribution is a continuous probability distribution described by a probability distribution function described here: http://mathworld.wolfram.com/NormalDistribution.html

The standard deviation of a random variable, statistical population, data set, or probability distribution is a measure of variation which correspond to the average distance from the mean of the data set to any given point of that dataset. It also corresponds to the square root of its variance.
A continuous variable is one for which, within the limits the variable ranges, any value is possible.
A categorical variable is a variable which that can only assume a finite number  of value and cast observation in a small number of categories.
A variable is a data item which can assume any of a set of values, either as determined by an agent or as randomly occuring through observation.

A regression model is a statistical model used in a type of analysis knowns as regression analysis, whereby a function is used to determine the relation between a response variable and an independent variable , with a set of unknown parameters.

It is a measure of how precise is an estimate of the statistical parameter is.Standard error is the estimated standard deviation of an estimate. It measures the uncertainty associated with the estimate. Compared with the standard deviations of the underlying distribution, which are usually unknown, standard errors can be calculated from observed data.

A regression coefficient is a data item generated by a type of data transformation called a regression, which aims to model a response variable by expression the predictor variables as part of a function where variable terms are modified by a number. A regression coefficient is one such number.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: An algorithm is an effective method expressed as a finite list of well-defined instructions for calculating a function.
An assocation is a relationship between two or more entities derived by some informational analysis.
A category is a class of entities having particular shared characteristics.
A central tendency measure is a central value or a typical value for a probability distribution.
A concept is term that refers to a generalization of a set of attributes or entities.
AND is a logical operator that has the value true if both of its operands are true, otherwise a value of false.

A control variable that is believed to alter the dependent or independent variables, but may not actually be the focus of the experiment. So that variable will be kept constant or monitored to try to minimise its effect on the experiment.
The number of elements of a finite set of objects.
Data analysis is a process of inspecting, cleaning, transforming, and modeling data with the goal of highlighting useful information, suggesting conclusions, and supporting decision making.
A definition is a description that succintly characterizes an entity.
A description is language entity in which elements of a language (formal or natural) are used to characterize an entity.
A dimensionless quantity is a quantity that has no associated unit.
Information content entity is an object that requires some background knowledge or procedure to correctly interpret.
An informational quality is a quality that pertains to information.
A language entity implements some language specification for the visual interpretation and is part of some document.
Likelihood is the hypothetical probability that an event that has already occurred would yield a specific outcome.
A logical operator is a unary or binary relation to construct logical expressions.
A mathematical entity is an information content entity that are components of a mathematical system or can be defined in mathematical terms.
A maximal value is largest value of an attribute for the entities in the defined set.
A mean is the central tendency of a collection of numbers taken as the sum of the numbers divided by the size of the collection.
A measurement value is a quantitative description that reflects the magnitude of some attribute.
A minimal value is smallest value of an attribute for the entities in the defined set.
A mode is the value that appears most often in a set of data.
A model is a representation of some thing.
A number is a mathematical object used to count, label, and measure.
An object is an entity that is wholly identifiable at any instant of time during which it exists.
A phrase is a group of words functioning as a single unit in the syntax of a sentence.

A process is an entity that is identifiable only through the unfolding of time, has temporal parts, and unless otherwise specified/predicted, cannot be identified from any instant of time in which it exists.
A quality is an attribute that is intrinsically associated with its bearer (or its parts), but whose presence/absence and observed/measured value may vary.
A quantity is an informational entity that gives the magnitude of a property.
A representation is a entity that in some way represents another entity (or attribute thereof).
A term is a word or phrase used to denote one or more entities.
A variable is a value that may change within the scope of a given problem or set of operations.

The Health Analysis Ontology includes attributes useful for informing analysis design, summarizing analysis results for later comparison, and for generating reports. It captures the data domain and analysis workflow in cartridges that represent domain knowledge, analytics knowledge, and other components of the analysis pipeline

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: An analysis question is a natural language description of what question a given analysis answers.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: Are higher exposure amounts of a risk factor significantly associated with the presence of heart disease?

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: An analysis workflow is a set of steps used to begin and complete an analysis. It includes defining the problem, preparing the data, training a statistical model, and representing the results.
Mean and standard-error-of-mean estimates for the entire cohort specified by cohort cartridge.
A binary variable is a variable taking values of 0 and 1.

A cadre is a probabilistic subpopulation produced by SCM. Cadres are similar to clusters, but they are identified via supervised learning and may incorporate feature selection or weighting in their definitions.
A cadre assignment function maps a subject record to a probability distribution characterizing that subject's probability of belonging to one of M cadres.
How many subpopulations the cohort specified by the cohort cartridge was divided into after conclusion of model-selection.
An index assigned to each subpopulation.
A cadre list contains the information of a list of cadres.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: A specialized kind of supervized cadre model technique that discovers sub-populations or cadres

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: How many observations each subpopulation contains.
The number of subjects in the training data assigned to each cadre.

A cartridge is the minimal necessary analysis components from the HAO are stored in modular serializations called cartridges. Given a KG, a cartridge is a subgraph containing application-specific  (in this case, analysis-specific) vocabularies that link to the KGâ€™s existing elements and extend the range of problems it may be applied to. In STA, cartridges are loaded and modifiedas the user chooses how to construct their risk analysis study.
The center of the cadre.
A code is a string sequence used to represent a constructed response variable in data tables.
A cohort cartridge lists the inclusion criteria used to determine if a given subject may be included in the userâ€™s study.
A component is a category of data tables in NHANES.
A condition is a mathematical definition of component of response variable definition, containing relationship, right-hand side, and left-hand side.
A conjunction is a mathematical operator used to combine expressions in response variable definitions.
In a subpopulation cartridge, this is the (survey-weighted) estimated mean of a covariate, calculated over the subjects in a specific subpopulation.
In a subpopulation cartridge, this is the (survey-weighted) standard error of the (survey-weighted) estimate of the mean of a covariate, calculated over the subjects in a specific subpopulation.
The elastic net mixing weight, a number between 0 and 1, controls whether a given parameter's regularization looks more like l1 regularization or l2 regularization.
Alpha d, the elastic net mixing weights for the d parameter.
Alpha W, the elastic net mixing weights for the W parameter.
A factor key is the prefix of the variable.
The name of the parameter d.
How to divide supplied features into cadre-assignment and target-prediction categories.
A file key is a character sequence mapping risk factor categories to data table filenames.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: Data table filenames containing 'ins' contain risk factor measurements of the category Organophosphate Insecticides

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Whether the cohort summary table is generated.
During model selection, a model is trained with every hyperparameter configuration, and a best model is chosen with respect to a supplied metric.
Each column of the parameter W defines a hyperplane which determines each cadre's target prediction function.
An input cartridge is a type of cartridge used to define input parameters / configurations when constructing a study.
Left-hand side of expression in response variable definitions

A left skewed data distribution is a characteristic of univariate random variables denoting some sort of asymmetry in distribution. Often indicated by having a mean less than the median, and a right-hand tail that is longer than the left-hand tail.
A metric describes how to choose the best model. For population health, this is the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC); for other problems, it could be (e.g.) generalization error.
Minimum number of positive observations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The hyperparameters used to train a model, the parameter estimates learned during training, and the rules by which it is applied to new observations.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A model cartridge assocatiated with a .pkl file gives the parameters and hyperparameters of the associated SCM. The SCM class contains methods to assign observations to new cadres.

A model parameter is a data item which is part of a model and which is meant to characterize an theoretical or unknown population. A model parameter may be estimated by considering the properties of samples presumably taken from the theoritecal population.
A note to describe the data in the file.
An output cartridge is a type of cartridge that stores an analysisâ€™ statistical findings and links to input cartridges used to define them.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: Results cartridge describing environmental risk factors for hypertension in obese women

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A parameters cartridge contains rules to complete the chosen analysis workflow.
A prediction weight bias parameter is a learnable parameter for the prediction model.
Right-hand side of expression in response variable definitions.
Regularization strength, a nonnegative number, controls the tradeoff between a model that is simple and one that fits the training data well.
Regularization strength for the d parameter.
Regularization strength for the W parameter.
Mathematical operator used in response variable definitions.
A response variable cartridge provides the analysis concepts and background domain axioms necessary to model a given disease

A result usually refers to an inference drawn from a statistical model. We often summarize the result of an association between a risk factor and a response variable with a coefficient estimate, standard error, and p-value.
A result count is the number of results.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Quantification of subpopulation-specific discovered associations between the risk factor and the response variable using regression coefficients, standard errors, and p-values

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A results cartridge is a type of output cartridge describing a single studyâ€™s statistical findings and constituent input cartridges.

A right skewed data distribution is a characteristic of univariate random variables denoting some sort of asymmetry in distribution. Often indicated by having a mean greater than the median, and a left-hand tail that is shorter than the right-hand tail.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: Most environmental exposure risk factor distributions

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A risk factor cartridge describes categories of semantically similar risk factors and details how they should be modeled.
Risk factor category is a category of similar potential risk factors, where 'similarity' is defined by domain experts.
The sharpness hyperparameter affects how quickly, as a subject's attributes shift, their cadre assignment function shifts.
The source of the cadre model
Mathematical transformation is applied to univariate random variables. The transformed distribution is shifted and scaled so it has a mean of zero and a variance of one.
An estimate is a coefficient from a statistical model quantifying the association between a risk factor and a response variable.
A study variable is a variable that potentially has a significant association with the response variable

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Summary statistics characterizing discovered subpopulations, including within-subpopulation variable means and rates.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A subpopulation cartridges gives 'Table 1s' (cohort-description tables) of discovered subpopulations.
Mean and standard-error-of-mean estimates for each discovered subpopulation.
The maximum number of stochastic gradient descent steps taken.

A target prediction function maps a subject record to a subpopulation-specific score. If the analysis problem is classification, the score gives that subject's risk of having a condition. If the analysis problem is regression, the score is a scaled estimate of the subject's response variable value.
A target variable is a variable used as response variable / target feature in modeling analyses
A threshold is the minimal value to show some significance exist.
Whether the study uses a cohort.
Whether the survey weight is used in the study.
